    "slug": "ccpa-business-obligations",
    "title": "CCPA Business Obligations",
    "summary": "Businesses subject to the CCPA/CPRA must satisfy notice requirements, maintain compliant privacy policies, impose contractual restrictions on service providers and contractors, and adhere to data minimization principles.",
    "domain": "CCPA/CPRA",
    "content": "# CCPA Business Obligations\n\n> Businesses subject to the CCPA/CPRA must satisfy notice requirements, maintain compliant privacy policies, impose contractual restrictions on service providers and contractors, and adhere to data minimization principles.\n\n## Key Points\n- Privacy policy must disclose categories of PI collected, purposes, third parties, and consumer rights; updated at least every 12 months (s 1798.130)\n- Notice must be provided at or before the point of collection (s 1798.100)\n- Service providers require written contracts prohibiting sale/sharing and restricting PI use to the direct business relationship (s 1798.140(ag))\n- Contractors (CPRA addition) have the same restrictions as service providers plus must allow compliance audits and provide contractual certification (s 1798.140(j))\n- Data minimization: collection and use must be reasonably necessary and proportionate to disclosed purposes\n- Businesses must respond to verifiable consumer requests within 45 days (extendable to 90)\n- A \"Do Not Sell or Share My Personal Information\" link is required on the homepage (s 1798.135)\n\n## Detail\n\n### Notice Requirements (ss 1798.100, 1798.130)\n\nBusinesses must provide consumers with:\n\n1. **Notice at collection:** At or before the point of collection, businesses must inform consumers of the categories of personal information being collected and the purposes for which each category will be used\n2. **Privacy policy:** A comprehensive privacy policy that discloses:\n   - Categories of personal information collected in the preceding 12 months\n   - Categories of sources from which PI is collected\n   - Business or commercial purpose for collecting, selling, or sharing PI\n   - Categories of third parties with whom PI is shared\n   - Specific pieces of PI collected (upon request)\n   - A description of each consumer right and how to exercise it\n   - Contact information for submitting requests\n3. **Update frequency:** The privacy policy must be updated at least every 12 months\n4. **Mandatory links:** The homepage must include a \"Do Not Sell or Share My Personal Information\" link (s 1798.135) and, if applicable, a \"Limit the Use of My Sensitive Personal Information\" link (s 1798.121)\n\n### Handling Consumer Requests (s 1798.130)\n\nWhen a business receives a verifiable consumer request:\n\n- **Response time:** 45 calendar days from receipt, extendable by an additional 45 days (90 total) when reasonably necessary, with notice to the consumer\n- **Verification:** The business must verify the identity of the requesting consumer\n- **Format:** Information must be delivered in a readily usable format; for data portability, in a structured, commonly used, machine-readable format\n- **Free of charge:** Responses provided at no cost to the consumer\n- **Request methods:** At minimum, businesses must provide a toll-free telephone number and, if the business operates a website, a web address for submitting requests\n\n### Service Provider Requirements (s 1798.140(ag))\n\nA service provider is a legal entity that processes personal information on behalf of a business pursuant to a written contract. Requirements:\n\n- **Written contract required** specifying the business purpose for which PI is provided\n- **Prohibited actions:** Must not sell or share PI received from the business\n- **Use restriction:** Must not retain, use, or disclose PI for any purpose outside the direct business relationship with the contracting business\n- **Deletion compliance:** Must comply with consumer deletion requests forwarded by the business\n- **No combining:** Must not combine PI received from the business with PI from other sources (except as permitted for the contracted service)\n\n### Contractor Requirements (s 1798.140(j)) -- CPRA Addition\n\nContractors are subject to the same restrictions as service providers, with additional requirements:\n\n- **Audit rights:** Must contractually agree to allow the business to audit the contractor's compliance\n- **Certification:** Must provide a contractual certification that they understand the restrictions and will comply with them\n- **Subcontractor flow-down:** Must notify the business if it engages any subcontractor to process PI and impose equivalent restrictions\n\n### Data Minimization (CPRA)\n\nCPRA introduced data minimization principles:\n\n- **Collection limitation:** A business's collection of personal information must be reasonably necessary and proportionate to the purposes for which the PI is collected or processed\n- **Purpose limitation:** PI must not be further processed in a manner incompatible with the disclosed purposes\n- **Retention limitation:** PI must not be retained longer than reasonably necessary for the disclosed purpose\n- **Use limitation:** Use of PI must be reasonably necessary and proportionate to achieve the purposes for which it was collected or processed\n\n### Enforcement Obligations\n\nBusinesses should also be aware of:\n\n- **Record-keeping:** Businesses that buy, sell, or share the PI of 10 million or more consumers must compile metrics on consumer requests received, complied with, and denied\n- **Risk assessments:** CPPA rulemaking authority (s 1798.185) authorizes regulations requiring risk assessments for processing that presents significant risk to consumer privacy\n- **Cybersecurity audits:** CPPA may require annual cybersecurity audits for businesses whose processing presents significant risk\n\n## Product Relevance\n- **privacy-mcp** checks privacy policies against CCPA business obligation requirements: presence of required disclosures (categories, purposes, rights descriptions), \"Do Not Sell or Share\" link detection, notice-at-collection language, and service provider/contractor disclosure. It flags missing required elements and outdated policies.\n\n## Cross-References\n- [[ccpa-overview]]\n- [[ccpa-consumer-rights]]\n- [[ccpa-sensitive-data]]\n- [[us-state-privacy-landscape]]\n\n## Sources\n- raw/regulations/ccpa-cpra-full-text.md\n",
