    "keyPoints": "- CCPA enacted June 28, 2018 (AB 375), effective January 1, 2020; CPRA passed November 3, 2020 (Proposition 24), operative January 1, 2023\n- Applies to for-profit entities doing business in California meeting any one of three thresholds: $25M revenue, 100,000+ consumers/households data, or 50%+ revenue from data sales\n- Establishes six consumer rights: know, delete, correct, opt-out of sale/sharing, limit sensitive PI use, and non-discrimination\n- CPRA created the California Privacy Protection Agency (CPPA) as an independent enforcement body, replacing the AG's primary enforcement role\n- CPRA eliminated the 30-day cure period for CPPA enforcement actions\n- Penalties: $2,500 per unintentional violation, $7,500 per intentional violation or violation involving minors under 16"
